choices.text:
: “The Narayongonj bridge has attracted some investors,” says Fakhrul, citing China, Thailand and Australia as examples. But with the usual ity, the bridge is yet to open. Such is the norm of the country. “The paved and pollution free road along with traffic lights at strategic locations of Dhaka is life changing,” says Shajreddeen, one of the consumers of Road Transport Authority’s (RTA) public bus service. “I hope all of us manage to cross our hands six months from now,” says Taher Ali, currently working in Comilla, a city in East Bangladesh. He is hopeful that the railway bridge

would be complete by that time.

Nahid Al Jazeera
